The objective of the project is to using 2 different clustering algorithms (Hierarchical and K-means) by using different distance measures (manhattan and euclidean in this report). After constructing the clusters, penalized logistic regression is applied.

Data Preparation

Musk dataset is included as data table. For both euclidean and manhattan methods, seperate matrices are created.To have better results, scaling operation is handled.

musk_datapath='Desktop/Musk1.csv'

musk1_raw = as.data.table(read.csv(musk_datapath),header = TRUE)

scaled_features = as.data.table(scale(musk1_raw[,3:ncol(musk1_raw)]))
musk1 = musk1_raw
musk1[,3:ncol(musk1)] = scaled_features
euc_dist = as.matrix(dist(scaled_features,"euclidean"))
man_dist = as.matrix(dist(scaled_features,"manhattan"))

K - medoids

Euclidean Distance

To see how many cluster is needed, elbow method is applied by using fviz_nbclust to get total sum of squares.

library(factoextra)
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Welcome! Related Books: `Practical Guide To Cluster Analysis in R` at https://goo.gl/13EFCZ
fviz_nbclust(scaled_features,FUN=kmeans,method="wss",diss=euc_dist)  # elbow point = 5. now do k medoids with 5

According to graph, the number of clusters should equal to 5.

The medoids are founded by using pam function. After finding the meoids, to calculate the distances to medoids, data table operations are made. The column names are changed and two data tables are merged.

medoid_euclidean = pam(scaled_features,k=5,metric='euclidean')
euc_dist = as.data.table(euc_dist)
euc_medoids = medoid_euclidean$id.med
euc_med_distances = euc_dist[,get(as.character(as.numeric(euc_medoids[1])))]
for(i in 2:5){
euc_med_distances<-cbind(euc_med_distances,euc_dist[,get(as.character(as.numeric(euc_medoids[i])))])
}
euc_med_distances<-as.data.table(euc_med_distances)
setnames(euc_med_distances,old=colnames(euc_med_distances),new=c("Center1","Center2","Center3","Center4","Center5"))

euc_med_bag = cbind(musk1_raw[,1:2],euc_med_distances)
colnames(euc_med_bag)=c("BagClass","BagID","C1","C2","C3","C4","C5")

For the third step, average distances of instances to centroids are measured.

euc_med_bag = as.data.table(euc_med_bag)
bag_average=aggregate(euc_med_bag,list(euc_med_bag$BagID),mean)
bag_average_woutgroup=bag_average[,-1]
colnames(bag_average_woutgroup)=c("BagClass","BagID","C1_AvgDist","C2_AvgDist","C3_AvgDist","C4_AvgDist","C5_AvgDist")

After finding the distances, logistic regression is applied to dataset.

To tune lambda, penalized package is recalled and optL1 function is deployed. After tuning the lambda, the model is fit to penald variable by using penalized function. That fitted model is then used for the prediction.

lambda1 <- optL1(bag_average_woutgroup$BagClass, penalized = ~., data = bag_average_woutgroup[,-1], 
                 fusedl = FALSE, minlambda1 = 0, maxlambda1 = 2, 
                 fold = 10)

penald <- penalized(bag_average_woutgroup$BagClass, penalized = ~., data = bag_average_woutgroup[,-1], 
                 lambda1 = lambda1$lambda, 
                 fusedl = FALSE)
prediction<-predict(penald,penalized=bag_average_woutgroup[,-1])
prediction

Since the predictions are made based on the logistic regression, the probabilities are assigned to classes and confusion matrix is contructed to see accuracy.

prediction[prediction>0.5]=1
prediction[prediction<=0.5]=0
prediction

confmatrix_keuc=confusionMatrix(as.factor(bag_average_woutgroup$BagClass),as.factor(prediction))
confmatrix_keuc

For the cross validation and predictions following steps are applied. Resulting parameters are kept in to result data table.

set.seed(133)
train_class = bag_average_woutgroup$BagClass
indices=generateCVRuns(as.factor(train_class),1,10,stratified=TRUE)
auc_crossvalid<-rep(NA,10)
traindata_wclass=cbind(train_class,bag_average_woutgroup[,-1])

for (i in 1:10) {
  Replication=indices[[1]]
  testindices=Replication[[i]]
  train=traindata_wclass[-testindices,]        
  test=traindata_wclass[testindices,]
  train_classes<-train$train_class
  
  prediction=predict(penald,penalized=test[,2:7])
  
  for (k in 1:length(prediction)) {
    if (prediction[k] < 0.5) {
      prediction[k] = 0
    } else {
      prediction[k] = 1
    }
  }
  
  roc_obj <- roc(test$train_class, prediction)
  auc_crossvalid[i] = auc(roc_obj)
}
mean(auc_crossvalid)
result = rbind(result, data.table(Clustering_Method="K-medoid",K = "5",Best_Lambda=lambda$lambda.min, AUC=mean(auc_crossvalid),Distance="euclidean",linkage=NA ))

fviz_nbclust(scaled_features,FUN=kmeans,method="wss",diss=man_dist)  # elbow point = 5. now do k medoids with 5

Hierarchical Clustering

Euclidean Distance

Same procedures are applied. To see the required number of clusters, silhouette is deployed instead of wws. They provide same number with different interpretation

fviz_nbclust(scaled_features, FUN = hcut, method = "silhouette", diss = dist(scaled_features,method = "manhattan"))

For this case, 3 clusters are used and the resulting dendogram is:

hier_euc<-hclust(dist(scaled_features,"manhattan"),method="complete")
plot(hier_euc, xlab="Classes")  # bu onemlii

Centroids are calculated as follows:

hc_cluster<-cutree (hier_euc , 3)
centroids<-data.table()
for(z in 1:3){
  temp<-subset(musk_hc)
  temp<-temp[,3:168]
  if (nrow(temp)>=2){
    cent<-pam(temp,k = 1)
    centroids<-rbind(centroids,cent$medoids)
  } else {
    centroids<-rbind(centroids,temp) 
  }}
man_hc = centroids
man_hc_distances = man_dist[,get(as.character(as.numeric(man_hc[1])))]

After that point similar procedures are applied as k-means.

for(i in 2:3){
  
  man_hc_distances<-cbind(man_hc_distances,man_dist[,get(as.character(as.numeric(man_hc[i])))])
}
man_hc_distances<-as.data.table(man_hc_distances)
